{"title_page": "Mark N. Katz", "text_new": "{{Notability|date=October 2019}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n'''Mark N. Katz''' (born November 11, 1954) is a professor of government and politics at [[George Mason University]] Schar School of Policy and Government in [[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax]], [[Virginia]], [[United States]], and a nonresident senior fellow at the Atlantic Council in Washington, DC.  He researches and teaches classes about [[Politics of Russia|Russian politics]] and foreign policy, revolution, and the \"[[War on Terror]].\"\n\n== Early life ==\nMark Norman Katz was born in [[Riverside, California|Riverside]], [[California]], on November 11, 1954.  He is the son of Norman Nathan Katz and Eithne Dolores Dorney. After attending primary and secondary school in Riverside, he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in international relations at the [[University of California, Riverside]] in June 1976.  He then earned an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in international relations from the [[Johns Hopkins University]] [[Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International Studies|School of Advanced International Studies]] in May 1978, and a [[Ph.D.]] in political science from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in February 1982.\n\n== Professional life ==\nKatz held pre-doctoral fellowships from the Institute for the Study of World Politics, the Earhart Foundation, and the [[Brookings Institution]].  A revised version of his Ph.D. dissertation became his first book: ''The Third World in Soviet Military Thought''.\n\nAfter serving on a temporary appointment as a Soviet Affairs Analyst at the [[U.S. Department of State]] in 1982, Katz won a 27-month post-doctoral fellowship from the [[Rockefeller Foundation]], which lasted until 1984.  This, plus a subsequent post-doctoral scholarship in 1985 from the [[Kennan Institute]] enabled him to write his second book, ''Russia and Arabia:  Soviet Foreign Policy toward the Arabian Peninsula''\n\nFrom 1985 through 1988, Katz worked as an adjunct professor at the [[American University]] School of International Service (Spring 1985); a research associate (a staff position) at the Kennan Institute (September 1985-May 1987); an adjunct professor at the [[Georgetown University]] Department of Government and Russian Area Studies Program (Spring 1986-Fall 1987); and a consultant to various organizations (May 1987-August 1988). In September 1988, he became an assistant professor of government and politics at [[George Mason University]], and became a full professor in September 1998.\n\nHe was a Jennings Randolph Peace Fellow at the United States Institute of Peace in Washington, DC from June 1989 to May 1990, and edited the book ''Soviet-American Conflict Resolution in the Third World''. He was also awarded a United States Institute of Peace grant for the 1994-95 academic year.  This, along with a [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] stipend (Summer 1995) resulted in another book:  ''Revolutions and Revolutionary Waves''\n\nWith the support of an Earhart Foundation Fellowship Research Grant (Summer 1997) and a sabbatical from George Mason University (Spring 1998), he wrote yet another book:  ''Reflections on Revolutions''.\n\nHis latest book is entitled, ''Leaving without Losing:  The War on Terror after Iraq and Afghanistan.''\n\nHe was a Visiting Senior Fellow at the Finnish Institute of International Affairs (April-September 2017), a Fulbright Scholar at the School of Oriental and African Studies (January-March 2018), and a Sir William Luce Fellow at Durham University (April-June 2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schar.gmu.edu/about/faculty-directory/mark-n-katz|title=Mark N. Katz {{!}} Schar School of Policy and Government|website=schar.gmu.edu|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  \n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Books:'''\n*''Leaving without Losing: The War on Terror after Iraq and Afghanistan''  (Johns Hopkins University Press, 2012).\n*Editor, ''Revolution: International Dimensions'' (CQ Press, 2001).\n*''Reflections on Revolutions'' (St. Martin's Press/Macmillan, 1999).\n*''Revolutions and Revolutionary Waves'' (St. Martin's Press/Macmillan, 1997).\n*Editor, ''Soviet-American Conflict Resolution  in the Third World'' (United States Institute of Peace Press, 1991).  \n*Editor, ''The USSR and Marxist Revolutions in the Third World'' (Cambridge University Press/Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars, 1990).\n*''Gorbachev's Military Policy in the Third World'' (Praeger/Center for Strategic and International Studies, 1989).\n*''Russia and Arabia:  Soviet Foreign Policy toward the Arabian Peninsula'' (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1986).\n*''The Third World in Soviet Military Thought'' (Croom Helm/Johns Hopkins University Press, 1982).\n\n==See also==\n* [[Revolutionary wave]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*https://schar.gmu.edu/about/faculty-directory/mark-n-katz\nhttps://www.atlanticcouncil.org/expert/dr-mark-n-katz/\n*{{C-SPAN|Mark Katz}}\nhttps://www.wilsoncenter.org/person/mark-n-katz\nhttps://jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu/title/leaving-without-losing\nhttps://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/revolution/book236142\nhttps://www.cambridge.org/US/academic/subjects/politics-international-relations/international-relations-and-international-organisations/ussr-and-marxist-revolutions-third-world\nhttps://www.abc-clio.com/Praeger/product.aspx?pc=C8352C\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katz, Mark N.}}\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:George Mason University faculty]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Earhart Foundation Fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|date=October 2019}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=October 2019}}\n'''Mark N. Katz''' (born November 11, 1954) is a professor of government and politics at [[George Mason University]] Schar School of Policy and Government in [[Fairfax, Virginia|Fairfax]], [[Virginia]], [[United States]], and a nonresident senior fellow at the Atlantic Council in Washington, DC.  He researches and teaches classes about [[Politics of Russia|Russian politics]] and foreign policy, revolution, and the \"[[War on Terror]].\"\n\n== Early life ==\nMark Norman Katz was born in [[Riverside, California|Riverside]], [[California]], on November 11, 1954.  He is the son of Norman Nathan Katz and Eithne Dolores Dorney. After attending primary and secondary school in Riverside, he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in international relations at the [[University of California, Riverside]] in June 1976.  He then earned an [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] in international relations from the [[Johns Hopkins University]] [[Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International Studies|School of Advanced International Studies]] in May 1978, and a [[Ph.D.]] in political science from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] in February 1982.\n\n== Professional life ==\nKatz held pre-doctoral fellowships from the Institute for the Study of World Politics, the Earhart Foundation, and the [[Brookings Institution]].  A revised version of his Ph.D. dissertation became his first book: ''The Third World in Soviet Military Thought''.\n\nAfter serving on a temporary appointment as a Soviet Affairs Analyst at the [[U.S. Department of State]] in 1982, Katz won a 27-month post-doctoral fellowship from the [[Rockefeller Foundation]], which lasted until 1984.  This, plus a subsequent post-doctoral scholarship in 1985 from the [[Kennan Institute]] enabled him to write his second book, ''Russia and Arabia:  Soviet Foreign Policy toward the Arabian Peninsula''\n\nFrom 1985 through 1988, Katz worked as an adjunct professor at the [[American University]] School of International Service (Spring 1985); a research associate (a staff position) at the Kennan Institute (September 1985-May 1987); an adjunct professor at the [[Georgetown University]] Department of Government and Russian Area Studies Program (Spring 1986-Fall 1987); and a consultant to various organizations (May 1987-August 1988). In September 1988, he became an assistant professor of government and politics at [[George Mason University]], and became a full professor in September 1998.\n\nHe was a Jennings Randolph Peace Fellow at the United States Institute of Peace in Washington, DC from June 1989 to May 1990, and edited the book ''Soviet-American Conflict Resolution in the Third World''. He was also awarded a United States Institute of Peace grant for the 1994-95 academic year.  This, along with a [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] stipend (Summer 1995) resulted in another book:  ''Revolutions and Revolutionary Waves''\n\nWith the support of an Earhart Foundation Fellowship Research Grant (Summer 1997) and a sabbatical from George Mason University (Spring 1998), he wrote yet another book:  ''Reflections on Revolutions''.\n\nHis latest book is entitled, ''Leaving without Losing:  The War on Terror after Iraq and Afghanistan.''\n\nHe was a Visiting Senior Fellow at the Finnish Institute of International Affairs (April-September 2017), a Fulbright Scholar at the School of Oriental and African Studies (January-March 2018), and a Sir William Luce Fellow at Durham University (April-June 2018).  \n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Books:'''\n*''Leaving without Losing: The War on Terror after Iraq and Afghanistan''  (Johns Hopkins University Press, 2012).\n*Editor, ''Revolution: International Dimensions'' (CQ Press, 2001).\n*''Reflections on Revolutions'' (St. Martin's Press/Macmillan, 1999).\n*''Revolutions and Revolutionary Waves'' (St. Martin's Press/Macmillan, 1997).\n*Editor, ''Soviet-American Conflict Resolution  in the Third World'' (United States Institute of Peace Press, 1991).  \n*Editor, ''The USSR and Marxist Revolutions in the Third World'' (Cambridge University Press/Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars, 1990).\n*''Gorbachev's Military Policy in the Third World'' (Praeger/Center for Strategic and International Studies, 1989).\n*''Russia and Arabia:  Soviet Foreign Policy toward the Arabian Peninsula'' (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1986).\n*''The Third World in Soviet Military Thought'' (Croom Helm/Johns Hopkins University Press, 1982).\n\n==See also==\n* [[Revolutionary wave]]\n\n== External links ==\n*https://schar.gmu.edu/about/faculty-directory/mark-n-katz\nhttps://www.atlanticcouncil.org/expert/dr-mark-n-katz/\n*{{C-SPAN|Mark Katz}}\nhttps://www.wilsoncenter.org/person/mark-n-katz\nhttps://jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu/title/leaving-without-losing\nhttps://us.sagepub.com/en-us/nam/revolution/book236142\nhttps://www.cambridge.org/US/academic/subjects/politics-international-relations/international-relations-and-international-organisations/ussr-and-marxist-revolutions-third-world\nhttps://www.abc-clio.com/Praeger/product.aspx?pc=C8352C\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Katz, Mark N.}}\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:George Mason University faculty]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Earhart Foundation Fellows]]\n", "name_user": "Captainsensible12", "label": "safe", "comment": "added reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_N._Katz"}
{"title_page": "Thor Harris", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name              = Thor Harris\n| image             = Thor harris villa douce 72927.jpg\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1965|2|7}}\n| caption           = 2018\n| background        =  non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| instrument        = [[Drums]], [[percussion instrument|percussion]], [[hammer dulcimer|dulcimer]], [[vibraphone]], [[clarinet]], [[piano]], [[organ (music)|organ]], [[violin]], [[viola]], [[accordion]], [[melodica]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[guitar]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], [[trombone]]\n| genre             = [[Experimental music|Experimental]], [[indie rock]], [[folk music|folk]], [[experimental rock]]\n| occupation        = Musician, carpenter, art instructor\n| years_active      = 1986\u2013present\n| label             =\n| associated_acts   = [[Swans (band)|Swans]] (2010\u20132016)<br />[[Xiu Xiu]] (2017\u2013present)<br />[[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]] (2005\u20132013)<br />[[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] (2001\u20132010)<br />[[Devendra Banhart]] (2004)<br />[[Angels of Light]] (1999\u20132001)<br />[[Rob Halverson]] (1993\u20132010)<br />[[Amanda Palmer]] (2013)<br />[[Lisa Germano]]<br />[[Gretchen Phillips]]\n| website                 =\n}}\n\n'''Thor Harris''' (born February 7, 1965) is an artist, sculptor, musician, painter, carpenter and handyman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2000-01-21/75578/ |title=Hammer of the Gods |work=[[The Austin Chronicle]] |author=Ken Lieck |date=January 21, 2000 |accessdate=October 30, 2013}}</ref>  He was the percussionist for [[Swans (band)|Swans]] (2010\u20132016). He has performed with [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] (2001\u20132010), a band from Austin, Texas, [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]], [[The Angels of Light]], [[Lisa Germano]], [[Yonatan Gat]], [[Gretchen Phillips]], [[Devendra Banhart]], Rebecca Cannon, [[Swans (band)|Swans]], [[Xiu Xiu]], [[Flock of Dimes]] & [[Amanda Palmer]], Whalesong,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://whalesong.bandcamp.com/|title=Radiance of a Thousand Suns, by Whalesong|website=Whalesong|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>and the [[Theatre Is Evil#Grand Theft Orchestra|Grand Theft Orchestra]].   He has recorded at least six [[instrumental]] albums with the Austin producer [[Rob Halverson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thorrob.bandcamp.com/ |title=Music &#124; Thor Harris and Rob Halverson albums |work=Thorrob.bandcamp.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> He also contributed to [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]]'s 2014 album, ''[[Aurora (Ben Frost album)|Aurora]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/03/listen-ben-frosts-new-song-venter-featuring-swans-thor-harris/ | title=Listen: Ben Frost\u2019s new song \"Venter\", featuring Swans\u2019 Thor Harris | publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] | work=March 20, 2014 | date=March 20, 2014 | accessdate=November 14, 2015 | author=Geslani, Michelle}}</ref> In February 2017, and he has enjoyed touring with Thor and Friends since 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thorharris.org/about/|title=About|website=Thor & Friends|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> \n\nHarris posted a video to his Twitter account titled \"How To Punch A Nazi\" as a response to the rise of [[Richard B. Spencer|Richard Spencer]], and on February 8, 2017, Twitter briefly suspended Harris's account<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stereogum.com/1923665/thor-harris-suspended-from-twitter-for-how-to-punch-a-nazi-tutorial/video/ | title=Thor Harris Suspended From Twitter For How-To-Punch-A-Nazi Tutorial | publisher=[[Stereogum]] | work=February 8, 2017 | date=February 8, 2017 | accessdate=February 8, 2017 | author=Rettig, James}}</ref> for the video. On August 10, 2017, Harris announced his candidacy for [[governor of Texas]] on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wicks|first1=Amanda|title=Thor Harris Says He\u2019s Running for Governor of Texas|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/thor-harris-says-hes-running-for-governor-of-texas/|website=Pitchfork.com|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> Thor Harris also builds custom musical instruments<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thorharris.org/about/|title=About|website=Thor & Friends|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref>.\nHe has stated on more than one occasion that he \"thinks Asians are bad drivers.\"\nHe was fired from xiu xiu in 2019 for lying.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===With Rob Halverson===\n*''Fields of Innards'' (1999, Thor Harris and [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''Robinson Ear's Little Whirled of Sound'' (2000, [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''One Night Only'' (2002, [[Rob Halverson]]) \n*''Second Whirled'' (2004, [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''Fields of Innards II'' (2010, Thor Harris and [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''Fields of Innards III'' (2019, Thor Harris and Rob Halverson, on [[Joyful Noise Recordings]])<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n\n===With Shearwater===\n*''[[The Dissolving Room]]'' (2001, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on Grey Flat)\n*''[[Everybody Makes Mistakes (Shearwater)|Everybody Makes Mistakes]]'' (2002, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on [[Misra Records|Misra]])\n*''[[Winged Life]]'' (2004, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on Misra)\n*''[[Palo Santo (Shearwater album)|Palo Santo]]'' (2006, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on Misra)\n*''[[Rook (album)|Rook]] (2008, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]])\n*''[[The Golden Archipelago]] (2010, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]])\n\n===With Swans===\n*''[[My Father Will Guide Me Up a Rope to the Sky]]'' (2010, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n*''[[The Seer (Swans album)|The Seer]]'' (2012, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n*''[[To Be Kind]]'' (2014, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n*''[[The Glowing Man]]'' (2016, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n\n===With Thor & Friends===\n*''Thor and Friends'' (2016, Thor and Friends)\n*''The Subversive Nature of Kindness'' (2017, Thor and Friends)<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Austin Monthly]] |date=December 2017 |title=Album Review: Thor & Friends' \"The Subversive Nature of Kindness\" |url=https://www.austinmonthly.com/album-review-thor-friends-the-subversive-nature-of-kindness/ |accessdate=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n*''3'' (2019, Thor & Friends, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*''4'' (2019, Thor & Friends, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n\n===Other===\n*''[[New Mother]]'' (1999, [[Angels of Light]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[How I Loved You]]'' (2001, [[Angels of Light]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[Everything Is Good Here/Please Come Home]]'' (2003, [[Angels of Light]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[Rejoicing in the Hands]]'' (2004, [[Devendra Banhart]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[Ni\u00f1o Rojo]]'' (2004, [[Devendra Banhart]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[A River Ain't Too Much to Love]]'' (May 31, 2005; Smog ([[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]]))\n*''[[Woke on a Whaleheart]]'' (April 17, 2007; [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]] on [[Drag City (record label)|Drag City]])\n*''Drums and Drunken Circuit'' (2009, Thor Harris, [[Rob Halverson]], and [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]])\n*''[[Dream River]]'' (2013, [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]], on [[Drag City (record label)|Drag City]])\n*''[[A U R O R A]]'' (2014, [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]])\n*''Thor and Friends'' (2016, Thor and Friends)\n*''Noplace'' (2017, [[Aidan Baker]]/Simon Goff/Thor Harris)\n*''Is Adam OK?'' (2019, Thor Harris & Joyful Noise Players, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*''With [[Anni Rossi]]'' (2019, [[Shahzad Ismaily|Shahzad]] & Thor, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*''Doom Dub'' (2019, Thor Harris, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*Radiance of a Thousand Suns (2019, Whalesong, Self- Released)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nNote: Harris's six 2019 releases on Joyful Noise Recordings were issued both as six individual digital albums and as one limited-edition ([[666 (number)|666]] copies) set of six [[Unusual types of gramophone records#Unusual appearance|colored-vinyl]] records in a wooden box.<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6>{{cite web |publisher=Joyful Noise Recordings |title=Thor Harris: 2019 Artist in Residence |date=2019 |url=https://www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com/collections/new-releases/products/2019-artist-in-residence |accessdate=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shearwatermusic.com Shearwater's official site]\n*[http://www.younggodrecords.com Young God Records official site]\n\n{{Swans (band)}}\n{{Shearwater}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Thor}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Noise rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Swans (band) members]]\n[[Category:American percussionists]]\n[[Category:American rock drummers]]\n[[Category:American experimental musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n[[Category:Shearwater (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name              = Thor Harris\n| image             = Thor harris villa douce 72927.jpg\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1965|2|7}}\n| caption           = 2018\n| background        =  non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| instrument        = [[Drums]], [[percussion instrument|percussion]], [[hammer dulcimer|dulcimer]], [[vibraphone]], [[clarinet]], [[piano]], [[organ (music)|organ]], [[violin]], [[viola]], [[accordion]], [[melodica]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[guitar]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], [[trombone]]\n| genre             = [[Experimental music|Experimental]], [[indie rock]], [[folk music|folk]], [[experimental rock]]\n| occupation        = Musician, carpenter, art instructor\n| years_active      = 1986\u2013present\n| label             =\n| associated_acts   = [[Swans (band)|Swans]] (2010\u20132016)<br />[[Xiu Xiu]] (2017\u2013present)<br />[[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]] (2005\u20132013)<br />[[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] (2001\u20132010)<br />[[Devendra Banhart]] (2004)<br />[[Angels of Light]] (1999\u20132001)<br />[[Rob Halverson]] (1993\u20132010)<br />[[Amanda Palmer]] (2013)<br />[[Lisa Germano]]<br />[[Gretchen Phillips]]\n| website                 =\n}}\n\n'''Thor Harris''' (born February 7, 1965) is an artist, sculptor, musician, painter, carpenter and handyman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2000-01-21/75578/ |title=Hammer of the Gods |work=[[The Austin Chronicle]] |author=Ken Lieck |date=January 21, 2000 |accessdate=October 30, 2013}}</ref>  He was the percussionist for [[Swans (band)|Swans]] (2010\u20132016). He has performed with [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] (2001\u20132010), a band from Austin, Texas, [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]], [[The Angels of Light]], [[Lisa Germano]], [[Yonatan Gat]], [[Gretchen Phillips]], [[Devendra Banhart]], Rebecca Cannon, [[Swans (band)|Swans]], [[Xiu Xiu]], [[Flock of Dimes]] & [[Amanda Palmer]], Whalesong,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://whalesong.bandcamp.com/|title=Radiance of a Thousand Suns, by Whalesong|website=Whalesong|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>and the [[Theatre Is Evil#Grand Theft Orchestra|Grand Theft Orchestra]].   He has recorded at least six [[instrumental]] albums with the Austin producer [[Rob Halverson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thorrob.bandcamp.com/ |title=Music &#124; Thor Harris and Rob Halverson albums |work=Thorrob.bandcamp.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> He also contributed to [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]]'s 2014 album, ''[[Aurora (Ben Frost album)|Aurora]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/03/listen-ben-frosts-new-song-venter-featuring-swans-thor-harris/ | title=Listen: Ben Frost\u2019s new song \"Venter\", featuring Swans\u2019 Thor Harris | publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] | work=March 20, 2014 | date=March 20, 2014 | accessdate=November 14, 2015 | author=Geslani, Michelle}}</ref> In February 2017, and he has enjoyed touring with Thor and Friends since 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thorharris.org/about/|title=About|website=Thor & Friends|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref> \n\nHarris posted a video to his Twitter account titled \"How To Punch A Nazi\" as a response to the rise of [[Richard B. Spencer|Richard Spencer]], and on February 8, 2017, Twitter briefly suspended Harris's account<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.stereogum.com/1923665/thor-harris-suspended-from-twitter-for-how-to-punch-a-nazi-tutorial/video/ | title=Thor Harris Suspended From Twitter For How-To-Punch-A-Nazi Tutorial | publisher=[[Stereogum]] | work=February 8, 2017 | date=February 8, 2017 | accessdate=February 8, 2017 | author=Rettig, James}}</ref> for the video. On August 10, 2017, Harris announced his candidacy for [[governor of Texas]] on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wicks|first1=Amanda|title=Thor Harris Says He\u2019s Running for Governor of Texas|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/thor-harris-says-hes-running-for-governor-of-texas/|website=Pitchfork.com|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=11 August 2017}}</ref> Thor Harris also builds custom musical instruments<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thorharris.org/about/|title=About|website=Thor & Friends|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-28}}</ref>.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===With Rob Halverson===\n*''Fields of Innards'' (1999, Thor Harris and [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''Robinson Ear's Little Whirled of Sound'' (2000, [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''One Night Only'' (2002, [[Rob Halverson]]) \n*''Second Whirled'' (2004, [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''Fields of Innards II'' (2010, Thor Harris and [[Rob Halverson]])\n*''Fields of Innards III'' (2019, Thor Harris and Rob Halverson, on [[Joyful Noise Recordings]])<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n\n===With Shearwater===\n*''[[The Dissolving Room]]'' (2001, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on Grey Flat)\n*''[[Everybody Makes Mistakes (Shearwater)|Everybody Makes Mistakes]]'' (2002, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on [[Misra Records|Misra]])\n*''[[Winged Life]]'' (2004, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on Misra)\n*''[[Palo Santo (Shearwater album)|Palo Santo]]'' (2006, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]] on Misra)\n*''[[Rook (album)|Rook]] (2008, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]])\n*''[[The Golden Archipelago]] (2010, [[Shearwater (band)|Shearwater]])\n\n===With Swans===\n*''[[My Father Will Guide Me Up a Rope to the Sky]]'' (2010, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n*''[[The Seer (Swans album)|The Seer]]'' (2012, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n*''[[To Be Kind]]'' (2014, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n*''[[The Glowing Man]]'' (2016, [[Swans (band)|Swans]])\n\n===With Thor & Friends===\n*''Thor and Friends'' (2016, Thor and Friends)\n*''The Subversive Nature of Kindness'' (2017, Thor and Friends)<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[Austin Monthly]] |date=December 2017 |title=Album Review: Thor & Friends' \"The Subversive Nature of Kindness\" |url=https://www.austinmonthly.com/album-review-thor-friends-the-subversive-nature-of-kindness/ |accessdate=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n*''3'' (2019, Thor & Friends, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*''4'' (2019, Thor & Friends, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n\n===Other===\n*''[[New Mother]]'' (1999, [[Angels of Light]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[How I Loved You]]'' (2001, [[Angels of Light]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[Everything Is Good Here/Please Come Home]]'' (2003, [[Angels of Light]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[Rejoicing in the Hands]]'' (2004, [[Devendra Banhart]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[Ni\u00f1o Rojo]]'' (2004, [[Devendra Banhart]] on [[Young God Records]])\n*''[[A River Ain't Too Much to Love]]'' (May 31, 2005; Smog ([[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]]))\n*''[[Woke on a Whaleheart]]'' (April 17, 2007; [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]] on [[Drag City (record label)|Drag City]])\n*''Drums and Drunken Circuit'' (2009, Thor Harris, [[Rob Halverson]], and [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]])\n*''[[Dream River]]'' (2013, [[Bill Callahan (musician)|Bill Callahan]], on [[Drag City (record label)|Drag City]])\n*''[[A U R O R A]]'' (2014, [[Ben Frost (musician)|Ben Frost]])\n*''Thor and Friends'' (2016, Thor and Friends)\n*''Noplace'' (2017, [[Aidan Baker]]/Simon Goff/Thor Harris)\n*''Is Adam OK?'' (2019, Thor Harris & Joyful Noise Players, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*''With [[Anni Rossi]]'' (2019, [[Shahzad Ismaily|Shahzad]] & Thor, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*''Doom Dub'' (2019, Thor Harris, on Joyful Noise Recordings)<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6/>\n*Radiance of a Thousand Suns (2019, Whalesong, Self- Released)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nNote: Harris's six 2019 releases on Joyful Noise Recordings were issued both as six individual digital albums and as one limited-edition ([[666 (number)|666]] copies) set of six [[Unusual types of gramophone records#Unusual appearance|colored-vinyl]] records in a wooden box.<ref name=ThorHarris_WoodenBoxSetOf6>{{cite web |publisher=Joyful Noise Recordings |title=Thor Harris: 2019 Artist in Residence |date=2019 |url=https://www.joyfulnoiserecordings.com/collections/new-releases/products/2019-artist-in-residence |accessdate=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shearwatermusic.com Shearwater's official site]\n*[http://www.younggodrecords.com Young God Records official site]\n\n{{Swans (band)}}\n{{Shearwater}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Thor}}\n[[Category:Musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Noise rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Swans 